SIMPLE: noxious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Noxious
<hw>Nox"ious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>noxius</ets>, fr. <ets>noxa</ets> harm; akin to <ets>nocere</ets>
to harm, hurt. Cf. <er>Nuisance</er>, <er>Necromancy</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Hurtful; harmful; baneful; pernicious; injurious;
destructive; unwholesome; insalubrious; <as>as, <ex>noxious</ex> air,
food, or climate</as>; pernicious; corrupting to morals; <as>as,
<ex>noxious</ex> practices or examples</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Too frequent an appearance in places of public resort is
<qex>noxious</qex> to spiritual promotions.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Guilty; criminal.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those who are <qex>noxious</qex> in the eye of the law.</q>
<rj><qau>Abp. Bramhall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Noisome; hurtful; harmful; injurious;
destructive; pernicious; mischievous; corrupting; baneful; unwholesome;
insalubrious. See <er>Noisome</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Nox"ious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Nox"ious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Noy</ent>⟦br⟧
